Bootstrap script that builds the CTX tooling binaries from an external sibling repo and copies them plus their prompt files into this project, since the template only scaffolds the project's own crates while the actual `ctx-*` tools live in the separate CTX repo this template was copied from.

It takes the CTX repo path as `$1`, falling back to `$CTX_REPO` env var, then `../CTX`; it validates that path by checking for `crates/ctx-context/Cargo.toml` and fails loudly (exit 1) if that's missing, rather than failing later with a confusing cargo error. It then runs `cargo build --quiet -p <pkg>...` inside that repo for the package list `(ctx-context ctx-scan ctx-verify ctx-cage ctx-summarize)`, and copies binaries from a *separate* list `(ctx-context ctx-scan ctx-verify ctx-cage ctx-run ctx-summarize)` into `target/debug/` — the lists differ because ctx-cage's Cargo.toml builds two binaries (`ctx-cage`, `ctx-run`) from one package. If a new package/binary is added to CTX, both `PACKAGES` and `BINARIES` here need updating or the new binary silently won't get installed.

It also copies `prompts/summarizer-leaf.md` and `prompts/summarizer-rollup.md` from the CTX repo into `./prompts/` in this project, because `ctx-scan`/`ctx-summarize` load these at runtime relative to cwd (project root), not from the tooling repo — so those prompt files must exist locally even though the binaries are elsewhere. Every run overwrites both binaries and prompts unconditionally (no version/staleness check); intended to be re-run whenever the template is freshly copied or the CTX repo updates. Uses `set -euo pipefail`, so any missing file or failed build aborts the whole script immediately. Depends on Claude Code's hook and `CLAUDE.md` both referencing these tools at the fixed path `target/debug/<name>` — moving the install location would break that coupling.